[2] Taiwan ex Thailand: imported case
Date: Sat 13 Aug 2016
Source: Focus Taiwan News Channel [edited]
http://focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201608130020.aspx


A 9-year-old boy was diagnosed with measles after returning to Taiwan from a trip to Thailand, and the Centers for Disease Control is urging people who have had contact with the boy to watch their health closely.

The CDC said in a news release Saturday [13 Aug 2016] that the boy traveled with his parents to Bangkok from [21 to 27 Jul 2016] and developed a fever and nausea 4 days after returning to Taiwan.

The boy was confirmed as having the measles on [11 Aug 2016], but he has since recovered and is out of quarantine.

During the boy's communicable period [4-12 Aug 2016], the boy visited a shopping center in Taipei, rode the high-speed rail and regular railway, and stayed at a Kaohsiung hotel.

The CDC has tracked 137 people who have had contact with the boy and will continue to monitor their health.

People who have come in contact with the boy are urged to watch their health for 18 days and wear surgical masks when seeking medical treatment if they develop suspicious symptoms.

Taiwan has reported 12 confirmed measles cases so far this year [2016]. Among them, 5 were indigenous ones, while 7 others were imported, with 2 of the cases originating in mainland China and one each in Hong Kong, Viet Nam, India, Japan and Thailand.

Taiwan recorded a total of 29 measles cases last year [2015], including 23 indigenous cases and 6 imported from mainland China.

[Byline: Chen Wei-ting and Lilian Wu]

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[Measles is a contagious viral illness that impacts millions of children in the Western Pacific Region. Although a safe vaccine has been available since 1963, measles remains a leading cause of childhood preventable death and disability. It is estimated that 20 000-30 000 deaths in the region are due to measles annually.

Measles is transmitted via droplets from the nose, mouth or throat of infected persons. Initial symptoms include high fever, runny nose, bloodshot eyes, and tiny white spots on the inside of the mouth. Several days later, a rash develops, starting on the face and upper neck and gradually spreading downward http://www.wpro.who.int/topics/measles/en/.

Anyone who is not protected against measles is at risk of getting infected when they travel internationally.

Before any international travel:
- Infants 6 months through 11 months of age should receive one dose of MMR vaccine.
- Children 12 months of age and older should receive 2 doses of MMR vaccine separated by at least 28 days.
- Teenagers and adults who do not have evidence of immunity against measles should get 2 doses of MMR vaccine separated by at least 28 days.
- Infants who get one dose of MMR vaccine before their 1st birthday should get 2 more doses (one dose at 12 through 15 months of age and another dose at least 28 days later).

Acceptable presumptive evidence of immunity against measles includes at least one of the following: written documentation of adequate vaccination, laboratory evidence of immunity, laboratory confirmation of measles, or birth in the United States before 1957 http://www.cdc.gov/measles/travelers.html. - Mod.ST]

For the HealthMap of Taiwan, see: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4416336,193.
For the HealthMap of Thailand, see: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4416336,151.]

